{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/sanskrit-shashti/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Aparna's Personal Space","author":"Aparna Ravindra"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"a0a02d15-978b-57f1-8549-e30a3f9dd3e8","excerpt":"Let's talk about the shashti vibhakti pratyaya today. This is called the \"possessive case\" in English. As the name says, it is used to show possession ownership‚Ä¶","html":"<p>Let's talk about the <em>shashti vibhakti pratyaya</em> today. This is called the \"possessive case\" in English. As the name says, it is used to show possession ownership or belonging.</p>\n<h4>How do you form or identify shashti vibhakti?</h4>\n<p>Most common formation of words in shashti vibhakti ends with -sya (-‡§∏‡•ç‡§Ø‚Äã) for masculine and nuetral forms. They end with -‡§Ø‡§æ: for faminine forms.\nExample:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">   ‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ‚Äã: -&gt; ‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ‡§∏‡•ç‡§Ø‚Äã\n   ‡§∏‡•Ä‡§§‡§æ -&gt; ‡§∏‡•Ä‡§§‡§æ‡§Ø‡§æ:\n   ‡§¶‡•á‡§µ‡•Ä -&gt; ‡§¶‡•á‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ:</code></pre></div>\n<h4>Commonly used words</h4>\n<p>Some special words we could remember and practice are:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">   ‡§∏‚Äã: -&gt; ‡§§‡§∏‡•ç‡§Ø‚Äã       ‡§∏‡§æ -&gt; ‡§§‡§∏‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ:\n   ‡§≠‡§µ‡§æ‡§®‡•ç -&gt; ‡§≠‡§µ‡§§‚Äã:     ‡§≠‡§µ‡§§‡•Ä -&gt; ‡§≠‡§µ‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ:\n</code></pre></div>\n<h4>First person and second person application</h4>\n<p>Remember that we praticed the sentence \"What is your name?\" earlier <a href=\"/blog/sanskrit-prathama\">here</a>? The word \"your\" is in shashti vibhakti. Do you remember the response to this question? When we say, \"<em>My</em> name is ____\",  \"<em>My</em>\" is again in shashti vibhakti. So, what are the forms then?</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">   ‡§Ö‡§π‡§Æ‡•ç -&gt; ‡§Æ‡§Æ‚Äã, ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§æ‡§Æ‡•ç -&gt; ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§Ø‡•ã:, ‡§µ‡§Ø‡§Æ‡•ç -&gt; ‡§Ö‡§∏‡•ç‡§Æ‡§æ‡§ï‡§Æ‡•ç\n   ‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§Æ‡•ç  -&gt; ‡§§‡§µ‚Äã, ‡§Ø‡•Å‡§µ‡§æ‡§Æ‡•ç -&gt; ‡§Ø‡•Å‡§µ‡§Ø‡•ã: , ‡§Ø‡•Ç‡§Ø‡§Æ‡•ç -&gt; ‡§Ø‡•Å‡§∑‡•ç‡§Æ‡§æ‡§ï‡§Æ‡•ç</code></pre></div>\n<h4>So are these the only forms? Of course not üòÜ</h4>\n<p>I learnt this from the Sanskrit class organised by <a href=\"https://sanskrit.today/course/bhasha-pravesha-1/\">sanskrit.today</a>. A very helpful table was shared by the teacher to practice and remember the forms of shashti vibhakti. Sharing it here (full credits to sanskrit.today).</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 970px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/a3e2a/shashti-table.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 46.09053497942387%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n          <source\n              srcset=\"/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/fc615/shashti-table.avif 243w,\n/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/b3175/shashti-table.avif 485w,\n/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/006d3/shashti-table.avif 970w,\n/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/b52ec/shashti-table.avif 1455w,\n/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/44c94/shashti-table.avif 1940w,\n/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/c646d/shashti-table.avif 3454w\"\n              sizes=\"(max-width: 970px) 100vw, 970px\"\n              type=\"image/avif\"\n            /><source\n              srcset=\"/blog/static/ed9e8f2dd75be1d1dcf68ddce024fd6b/0e3e2/shashti-table.